The 6 ITIL Service Value Chain Activities

[Plan]
  ↓
[Improve]
  ↓
[Engage]
  ↓
[Deliver and transition]
  ↓
[Obtain / Build]
  ↓
[Deliver & Support]



1️⃣ Plan

  Purpose:
  Ensure a shared understanding of the vision, current status, and direction for improvement.
  
  Key activities include:
  
  Strategy and roadmap planning
  
  Portfolio management
  
  Risk management
  
  Policies and standards

2️⃣ Improve

  Purpose:
  Ensure continuous improvement of services, practices, and products.
  
  Key activities include:
  
  Identifying improvement opportunities
  
  Measuring performance
  
  Implementing incremental improvements
  
  Using feedback and metrics
  
  This activity supports all other value chain activities.

3️⃣ Engage

Purpose:
Understand stakeholder needs and maintain good relationships.

  Key activities include:
  
  Managing customer and user relationships
  
  Gathering requirements and feedback
  
  Managing demand and expectations
  
  Communication and transparency

4️⃣ Design & Transition

Purpose:
Design new or changed services and ensure they are ready for live use.

  Key activities include:
  
  Service design
  
  Change enablement
  
  Release management
  
  Testing and validation
  
  Knowledge transfer

5️⃣ Obtain / Build

Purpose:
Create, acquire, or configure service components.

  Key activities include:
  
  Software development
  
  Infrastructure provisioning
  
  Vendor and supplier management
  
  Build and configuration activities

6️⃣ Deliver & Support

Purpose:
Ensure services are delivered and supported effectively.

  Key activities include:
  
  Service operations
  
  Incident management
  
  Request fulfillment
  
  Monitoring and event management
  
  User support
  
  How the Service Value Chain Works
  
  Activities are not linear
  
  Different value streams use different combinations of activities
  
  Each activity transforms inputs into outputs, creating value
